This is a 70-year-old gentleman with colon cancer based on outside pathology presenting for the below concerns:
#1 Colon adenocarcinoma in the transverse colon
He was asymptomatic till his surveillance colonoscopy.  He has an excellent functional status.  He has not undergone further staging evaluation.  We will pursue this further at this time.
#2 Postnasal drip
Will provide him with some Allegra and Flonase to see if this provides him symptomatic relief.
RECOMMENDATIONS
1.  Will pursue routine lab tests.
2.  Will obtain a CT abdomen and pelvis.  He is a getting chest x-ray, and we are going to be reviewing the outside pathology here.
3.  We will defer colonoscopy at this time, since the area in question was tattooed.
4.  He will follow-up with surgery and us after these tests are complete.
5.  Perioperative clearance.  He has not had difficulties with anesthesia previously.  He has no family history of adverse reactions to anesthesia or known bleeding disorder.  He does have open-angle glaucoma. He  had a recent EKG stress test on 5/13 that where his heart rate reached 80% of predicted and no evidence of ischemia was noted.  He would be a low-risk candidate for a moderate-risk procedure and would, otherwise, be cleared to undergo anesthesia.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

