[start section id="20103"]

This is a 70-year-old gentleman with a personal history of colon polyps presenting for the below concerns:
#1 Colon adenocarcinoma
Mr. Locher was in his usual state of health when he underwent screening colonoscopy May 7, 2010.  His last colonoscopy was five years ago.  At that time, he was noted to have a polyp, the details of which are unknown but prompted them to pursue another colonoscopy within five years.  During the colonoscopy, the prep was excellent.  They were able to make to the ileocecal valve.  They did note an 8-mm polyp in the cecum that was sessile; however, they were able to remove it with a hot snare completely.  In addition, they noted a 5-cm polypoid sessile mass in the transverse colon that was ulcerated.  Biopsy in the cecal lesion was consistent with a tubular adenoma; however, biopsy of the transverse colon ulcerated mass was consistent with invasive adenocarcinoma that was moderately well-differentiated.  The outside colonoscopy report did state that a tattoo was placed.
He has not undergone any other evaluations at-home for this.
He states that he has been feeling good.  He denies any symptoms such as abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, change in his bowel habits including constipation or change in his stool caliber, fatigue, weight-loss, hematochezia, melena, or hematemesis.
#2 Sore throat
This has been ongoing for the past two-weeks.  This has been associated with postnasal drip and a nonproductive cough.  Denies fevers, chills, sinus pressure, or purulent nasal drainage, just occasionally clear rhinorrhea.

[end section id="20103"]

